\f2\fs56 \cf2 Step 1 - Setup Git\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl576\sa600\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 The next command is the command that we'll run a single time so that our project will use git.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl576\sa600\partightenfactor0

\i \cf2 Again, we see the dollar sign ($), so we need to type this into the terminal window - without the actual dollar sign.
\i0 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl460\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs28 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 \shad0 $ git init\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl576\sa600\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \shad0 This gets everything in the current folder ready to be tracked by Git.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl460\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs28 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 \shad0 $ git add --all\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl576\sa600\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf2 \cb1 \strokec2 \shad0 This takes the first commit, or snapshot of our application code.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl460\partightenfactor0

\f3\fs28 \cf3 \cb4 \strokec3 \shad0 $ git commit -am "Initial commit"\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl840\sa200\partightenfactor0

